{
  "doc_id": "38866",
  "text": "Despite continued interest in the role of catecholamines in the processing of song [CITATION_1] , the mechanisms by which they modulate auditory responses in songbirds are not well understood. According to models developed in mammals, CA terminals may release transmitter in a tonic or paracrine fashion that is independent of both firing and external stimuli [CITATION_2] . This release may alter the responsivity or spontaneous firing activity in forebrain neurons [CITATION_3] and may be sustained over prolonged periods [CITATION_4] . Such release may drive sensory plasticity without stimulus-dependent firing or presynaptic regulation. In contrast, or in addition, catecholamine release may be driven by sensory stimuli. Neurons in both the NE and DA systems respond to a myriad of stimuli from multiple modalities [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Hearing conspecific song induces the expression of immediate early genes such as FOS and Egr-1, which mark new protein synthesis in response to a stimulus [CITATION_9] , in many CA regions. In male zebra finches (Taenopygia guttata), for example, exposure to a singing tutor induced FOS expression in the substantia nigra (SN), ventral tegmental area (VTA), and the periaqueductal gray (PAG), but this induction was found within DA neurons only in the PAG [CITATION_10] . Similarly, in estrogen-primed female white-throated sparrows, hearing conspecific male song induced Egr-1 expression in the locus coeruleus (LoC), SN, VTA, and PAG [28, unpublished data], but not in the tyrosine hydroxylase (TH)-positive cells of those areas [CITATION_11] . Gale and Perkel [CITATION_12] showed that in anesthetized male zebra finches, dopaminergic neurons in the SN and VTA fired in response to auditory stimuli, including conspecific song. Such responses may be limited, however, to the anesthetized state [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] . It is therefore unclear whether hearing conspecific song rapidly induces CA activity in awake individuals. In this study, we looked for evidence of rapid increases in catecholamine synthesis in auditory areas of sexually receptive females listening to conspecific male song.",
